arch:property.oc:show_val: L5 is fill above some mudbrick wall collapse and some ashy pits. We changed to this locus from L3 because L3 is a mix of crumbled mudbrick and a large ashy section. This locus is coming upon a more well defined wall, L7 that will need to be separated into more loci. We also opened L5 North of the L7 wall looking to see if the wall continued north, found a few more mudbricks. The closing elevations for the NE and NW are the closing elevations for the area north of the wall.

originally fill above L6 ashy fill and wall (L7), also expanded to fill above northern most bricks of the wall. Later opened L12 as fill north of the wall below the few mudbricks we found in the area.
ashy fill fine grained mixed w/ silty loam and chunks of mudbricks
mudbrick collapse, chunks of clay, burned pottery and clay, pebbles, rocks, plaster
L5 fill is mix between ash and mudbrick collapse on the south side of the wall L7, on the north side of the wall the locus is fill above more of the mudbricks associated with the wall.

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
